Feb 9 2009 	Very nice but in the middle of nowhere	I needed a place to stay overnight while in transit from a city in China's interior (from which I had flown that afternoon), on my way back to the U.S. (to which I would fly the next morning). I chose this hotel for its location very close to the Beijing Airport . . . less than 10 minutes' away. I paid 612 RMB including breakfast.Taxi fare from the Beijing Airport to the hotel was only 22 RMB. I always dread getting into a taxi at an airport for a short-distance ride (i.e., a very low fare for a driver who may have been in a queue for hours hoping for a high fare to the center of the city), but this driver did not seem to care . . . maybe they have a provision where they can cut to the front of the line when they go back to the airport if they had a short ride. The taxi driver got a little lost on the way over, but fortunately I had the hotel's phone number with me so showed it to him so he could phone and as it turned out we were only 2 minutes away from the point of the phone call.The hotel is very nice and modern; very clean, comfortable room with high quality bedding and luxurious bathroom. I was there during the Chinese New Year holiday (in Jan 2009) and as such the hotel was eerily empty. I suspect this is primarily a business hotel and no business is done during the CNY holiday; few people travel on leisure to cold Beijing in January, and if they did, few vacationers would opt to stay in the middle of an industrialized area way out by the airport.The staff was very friendly . . . the fitness center was quite nice - large with a big glass exterior window, with free weights, about 8 weight machines, about 3-4 tread mills, a couple of ellptical machines and a couple of stair climbers. Exercise machines had individual TVs and built-in fans. The fitness center also had a large pool (though I did not use it).I'm not a spa kind of guy, but they did have a special of 60-minute foot massage for only 99 RMB, so I tried it and it was very nice.Only two downsides to this hotel, neither of which is a big deal:1. Its remote location in the midst of an industrial park type of area; there are no shops or restaurants nearby or much of anything to see or look at should you want to have an interesting leisurely stroll. So, if you are averse to mini-bars as a source for a can of diet Coke or a candy bar, be forewarned you can't just walk down the street to a convenience store.2. The English of the staff is not great; the message light on my phone was blinking . . . the instruction was to push the button to retrieve messages . . . so I pushed the button which rang the switchboard and they could not figure out what I was wanting . . . eventually they picked up my saying the word &quot;message&quot; and they interpreted it as &quot;massage&quot; so they transferred me to the spa &amp; salon. So I went downstairs to speak to the front desk and they thought I was trying to tell them that my phone was broken. Uggh!!! I later discerned that my wife had called. But I had to put up with a blinking message lights on all 3 room phones for the rest of my stay (Overnight, I covered up the lights with paper).The hotel does offer a free shuttle bus on the hour to the airport, so I used this. I was the only one on the bus.TV had usual assortment of English channels that you find in Asia . . . e.g., CNN, CNBC Asia, HBO.	
